==Religion== Priestly practitioners of the Gurung Dharma include Ghyabri (Klehpri), Pachyu (Paju), and Bon Lamas.<ref name=Fuehrer>{{cite book|title=Tribal populations and cultures of the Indian subcontinent |volume=2 |issue=7 |first=Christoph |last=von Fürer-Haimendorf |authorlink=Christoph von Fürer-Haimendorf |pages=137–8 |publisher=[[Brill Publishers]] |year=1985 |ISBN=90-04-07120-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aRSOnRfPAq0C&pg=PA137 |accessdate=2011-04-02}}</ref> Shamanistic elements among the Gurungs remain strong and most Gurungs often embrace Buddhist and Bön rituals in communal activities.<ref name=Latham>{{cite book|title=Descriptive Ethnology |volume=I |author=[[Robert Gordon Latham]]|year=1859 |publisher=John Van Voorst, Paternoster Row |location=London |pages=80–82}}</ref><ref name=Mumford>{{cite book|title=Himalayan Dialogue: Tibetan Lamas and Gurung Shamans in Nepal |author=Mumford, Stanley Royal |pages=30–32 |year=1989 |publisher=University of Wisconsin Press |location=[[Madison, Wisconsin]] |isbn=0-299-11984-X}}</ref>
